MZINCHALEFT SESSION: THE DESCENT AND THE ESCAPE
Standalone Session Document — Begins in the Cognitorium
The party is inside the Cognitorium. They have met GEAR. They have explored the archive. Davinia has read the quarantine data-plates. The lore moments are done. What remains: the Falmer reading room (if they find it), the boss fight, and the escape.

THE COGNITORIUM — REMAINING EXPLORATION
THE ELDER READING ROOM
Location: A side chamber off the archive's lower ring. The door is open — this was not classified research. It was standard operating procedure.
Finding it: The party can discover this room during general exploration, or GEAR can lead them to it if anyone asks about the Cognitorium's other facilities. He does not volunteer it — not because he's hiding it, but because he considers it unremarkable. It was a tool. You don't give tours of the broom closet.
Read aloud:
"Off the main archive, through a brass archway, is a smaller circular chamber. It is not a library. It looks like a medical theater.
Six heavy chairs are arranged in a circle, facing inward toward a central pillar. The pillar is mounted with an intricate array of lenses, tuning forks, and a mechanical bracket designed to hold something cylindrical — unspooling it flat, like a scroll on a reading stand.
The chairs are equipped with thick leather restraints. Wrists. Chest. Head. A metal apparatus at each headrest is designed to hold the occupant's eyes open.
The floor around the chairs is stained. The stains are old — older than anything else in the Cognitorium, which is saying something. They have eaten into the bronze like acid. The restraints are the most worn objects in the entire ruin. Everything else in the Cognitorium looks like it was used once or twice. These restraints were used until the leather stretched and cracked and had to be replaced. Multiple times."
If they investigate (Guile or Magic TN 12): The bracket on the central pillar is designed to hold an Elder Scroll. The lenses and tuning forks are calibrated to record tonal frequencies produced by the reader during exposure. The restraints are sized for elves — slighter builds than Dwemer.
If they ask GEAR:
GEAR rolls over. His amber eye clicks as it focuses on the array.
"The Optical Translation Array! Yes, an excellent piece of engineering. The primary researchers determined early in the program that direct Elder Scroll exposure caused irreversible neurological collapse in Dwemer subjects. Unacceptable losses — trained tonal architects are difficult to replace.
The solution was elegant. The refugee population from the surface — the Snow Elves — provided a renewable source of biological processors. They were seated, restrained, and exposed to the Scroll's contents. The Array recorded the tonal frequencies of their cognitive collapse in real-time, allowing our researchers to extract mathematical data from the Scroll without personal exposure.
The biological processors experienced total optic nerve destruction within 3-7 exposures, followed by progressive neurological degradation. They were then relocated to the subsurface maintenance tunnels for manual labour duties until biological failure.
An efficient system! The data yield per unit was quite impressive."
He says all of this in the same helpful, chipper tone he uses for everything.
What this means: The Falmer weren't just poisoned by mushrooms. They were strapped to chairs and forced to read Elder Scrolls until their eyes burned out and their minds shattered, so the Dwemer could record the math of infinity using elven brains as disposable calculators. Then the blind, broken survivors were sent underground to work until they died.
This is not a horror room. To GEAR, this is an office. The horror is in the normality.
👁️ DAVINIA SEES: The residual intent baked into the chairs does not read SUFFER or PUNISH. It reads: EXTRACT. MEASURE. DISCARD. These chairs were not designed for cruelty. They were designed for data collection. The cruelty was incidental. The intent is purely utilitarian, and that's worse.
The faint aural residue of the victims looks like shattered glass — cognitive signatures that were whole when they sat down and fragmented when they stood up. Thousands of readings. Thousands of broken minds.
CROWN REACTION: Quiet. Then: "Efficient. The instrument breaks but the data is recorded." — Ismara's tone is not approving. It is recognizing a methodology she understands on a professional level. She does not say "this is what I would do." She doesn't have to.
🎵 ORION: If he uses Diagnostic Song on the restraints, he hears a layered, screaming dissonance — the tonal residue of minds being forced open and breaking. It's not one voice. It's thousands, compressed into a single chord of agony. His ears ring for a full minute afterward. The song taught him something he didn't want to know: tonal architecture isn't music. It's the mathematical restructuring of reality. The Dwemer used living minds as the friction surface for that math.
SAIJAH: The absence she felt in the city — no roots, no Kynareth, no connection to the natural world — is absolute in this room. Whatever happened here was so fundamentally divorced from the natural order that the Eldergleam's network doesn't just avoid this place. It doesn't acknowledge it exists. This room is a blind spot in the world's immune system.

THE WORKSHOP — CENTURION PRIME
Run the boss fight as written in the main module. All stats, mechanics, interactable objects, extraction rules, and character-specific notes apply. FP 200, DR 12, Shock ignores DR. Chest plate 30 HP, DR 0. Extraction Might TN 14, Kyboh Advantage.
The fight is the fight. It's solid. Don't change it.
WHEN THE CENTURION POWERS DOWN
"The Centurion doesn't fall. It slows. The hammer arm drops. The legs lock. The eye dims from bright to pale to nothing. Steam hisses from every joint as the internal pressure equalizes. It stands there — twelve feet of dead engineering, perfectly upright, as if it simply decided to stop.
From a crevice in the wall, a single Dwarven Spider Worker scuttles out. It ignores you completely. It climbs up the motionless leg of the Centurion, its manipulators clicking. It reaches the shattered chest plate. It probes the ruined hardware where the Matrix used to be. It tries to tighten a broken gear. It tries to seal a venting steam pipe.
Thirty seconds. It works for thirty seconds.
Then it stops. The spider climbs back down, movements slow, and retreats into the dark corner of the alcove. Waiting for a repair order that will never come."
GEAR floats over. His eye clicks as it focuses on the empty chest cavity.
"Oh dear. That is... suboptimal. The Primary Unit has ceased function. I will log a maintenance request."
Pause. The eye dims slightly.
"Though I suppose no one is coming to fulfill it. Are they."
Not a question.

THE MATRIX IN HAND
Kyboh holds the Matrix. It's warm. Body temperature. It pulses with a rhythm that reminds him of a heartbeat. Not his.
The party can catch their breath. Loot the workshop. Talk to GEAR. Discuss next steps.
There is no alarm. There is no urgency. The Cognitorium is quiet.
This is the last quiet moment they will have for a long time.

THE ESCAPE — THE INVERSION
THE TRIGGER
The alarm does not trigger when the Matrix is removed. It triggers when the party LEAVES THE WORKSHOP.
The moment the first character crosses the threshold of the workshop door back into the Cognitorium's internal staircase:
Read aloud:
"The amber lamps snap to crimson. Every light in the sphere — the archive, the staircase, the corridors — flashes from warm gold to a harsh, pulsing red. A sound builds in the walls. Not a siren. A TONE. A sustained, grinding, high-frequency vibration that you feel in your teeth, in the bones of your hands, in the fillings you didn't know you had. Every bronze pipe in the Cognitorium is screaming the same note.
Above you, in the walls and ceiling, the sound of heavy locks disengaging. Dozens of them. Simultaneously.
GEAR spins, his eye clicking rapidly between red and amber.
'Safe Integration Protocol has been terminated. System-wide biological purge activated. All non-authorized organic material will be eradicated.' He pauses. 'That would be you. I recommend we leave immediately. Current survival probability: 4.2%.'"
👁️ DAVINIA SEES: The entire Cognitorium shifts from dormant blue to a violent, thrashing web of angry red intent. Every wall, every pipe, every surface is lit with a single, unified directive: EXTIRPATE. The city isn't defending itself. It's cleaning an infection. The party IS the infection.
THE DESIGN — WHY THIS WORKS
The party walked INTO the dungeon with almost zero resistance. No traps at the surface. Janitor spiders that ignored them. A tonal puzzle that welcomed them. A city that lit up as they passed and dimmed as they left. The Cognitorium opened its doors.
The dungeon LET THEM IN. It was evaluating. GEAR activated because they passed the evaluation.
Now they've taken the Matrix — the central power regulator — and the evaluation is over. The entire ruin reclassifies them from AUTHORIZED to CONTAMINANT. Everything between them and the surface wants them dead.
Classic dungeon: Fight your way in, find the boss at the bottom, kill it, take the loot, walk out.
Mzinchaleft: Walk in unopposed, find the boss at the bottom, kill it, take the loot, fight your way out against everything you walked past on the way down.
The threat escalates in REVERSE. The hardest individual enemies are first (Cognitorium spheres). The lift is attrition. The city is a numbers game. The surface lift is a breakout under fire. Each phase is less dangerous per-enemy but more overwhelming in volume.

ESCAPE PHASE 1: THE COGNITORIUM GAUNTLET
Location: The internal staircase and archive level of the Cognitorium sphere. The party must get from the workshop (bottom of the sphere) to the docking port (top of the sphere) where the Deep Lift platform is waiting.
The threat: Dwemer Spheres. The Cognitorium's dedicated security constructs. These are not janitor spiders — they are purpose-built combat units that were dormant in wall alcoves throughout the archive.
The reveal: As the party climbs the spiral staircase, the walls OPEN. Bronze panels slide aside and Dwemer Spheres roll out, unfolding into their combat forms mid-stride. Two from the archive level. Two more from alcoves on the staircase itself.
