REACHING THE DOCKING PORT
When the last party member reaches Zone 3 (the docking port), they can activate the Deep Lift. The platform rises from the docking clamp with a hydraulic hiss. The Spheres pursuing up the staircase reach the port just as the platform begins to ascend — one Sphere lunges for the edge. A character can kick it off (Might TN 10) or it pulls itself aboard and must be dealt with on the lift.
The platform enters the shaft. The Cognitorium falls away below. Through the shaft opening, the party can see the Spheres gathering at the port, their crossbow arms tracking upward, bolts sparking off the shaft walls as the platform rises out of range.
Then the shaft walls close around them. Bronze. Ascending.

ESCAPE PHASE 2: THE DEEP LIFT — THE LONG CLIMB
Location: The 500-foot shaft between the Cognitorium (Blackreach) and the Mzinchaleft city level. The same shaft they descended through in wonder hours ago.
The problem: The lift takes a LONG time. On the way down, this was a spectacular descent through Blackreach's open cavern. On the way up, the shaft is ENCLOSED — bronze walls on all sides, the platform grinding upward at a mechanical pace that cannot be hurried. They are trapped on a 50-foot disc moving through a vertical tunnel full of maintenance hatches, exhaust vents, and access points that are now deploying hostiles.
The pacing: This is a sustained attrition sequence. Not a single fight — a gauntlet. The party cannot rest, cannot recover, and cannot speed up the lift. They endure or they die.
Run this as a cinematic action setpiece, like the ice floe crossing. Not strict turn-by-turn combat. The party acts collectively. Describe the waves, let players declare actions, resolve them with quick rolls, keep the momentum.
WAVE 1 — THE DROP (Minutes 0-5)
The shaft is enclosed. The Blackreach cavern is gone — just bronze walls sliding downward as they ascend. The crimson emergency lighting pulses in the shaft. The tonal alarm is a physical pressure in the enclosed space.
Then: maintenance hatches in the shaft wall BANG open. Two Dwemer Spiders drop onto the platform from above.
2× Dwemer Spider Sentinel (same stats as city spiders — FP 18, DR 5, Static Shock)
This is manageable. Two spiders on a 50-foot platform. The party should handle this quickly. The danger is FP drain — Static Shock costs 4 FP per hit, and they just fought a boss and a fighting retreat through Spheres.
⚠️ KYBOH: If he still has the Anchor, Static Shock FP drain fails against him. He's the shield.
GEAR: "Maintenance units repurposed for combat duty! A creative allocation of resources. Their Static Shock is calibrated to disable organic neural pathways. I recommend not being hit."
WAVE 2 — THE VENTS (Minutes 5-12)
The lift passes a section of shaft lined with exhaust vents — horizontal openings in the bronze walls, each about two feet wide. As the platform rises past them, spider legs reach out. Spiders are INSIDE the vents, firing Static Shock through the openings but not fully emerging.
The hazard: 4 vents pass the platform over 3 rounds. Each vent contains a spider that fires one Static Shock (3 damage + 4 FP drain) at a random party member as the platform passes.
The counter: Characters with ranged attacks can destroy the spiders in the vents before they fire (Agility TN 12 to target the narrow opening). Davinia can ice-wall a vent shut. Orion can play a dissonant note into a vent that scrambles the spider inside (Tonal Engineering TN 12, disables one vent). Kyboh can physically block shots with his body if he has the Anchor (no FP drain).
GEAR: "The exhaust vents are 0.6 meters wide. Insufficient for Sphere deployment. The system is compensating with the available units. Resourceful! Survival probability: 6.1%. An improvement!"
WAVE 3 — THE BOARDERS (Minutes 12-20)
The platform shudders. From BELOW — spiders are climbing the lift mechanism itself. The underside of the platform. Manipulator legs punch through the grating, grasping at ankles, sparking with electrical discharge.
The hazard: Spiders are cutting through the floor grating. Each round, one section of the platform (a 10-foot square) becomes UNSAFE — standing on it means an Agility TN 14 check or take 5 damage as the grating gives way and a spider grabs your leg.
The counter: Characters can stomp spiders back through the grating (Might TN 10, satisfying crunch), seal sections with ice (Davinia), or rip grating sections up to use as improvised barriers. The platform gets progressively smaller as safe footing shrinks.
GEAR: Rolls to the platform edge and peers over. "They are ascending the support pylons. Twelve... fourteen... seventeen units. They will breach the platform surface in approximately ninety seconds. May I suggest violence?"
GEAR can use Tonal Pulse here — the 10ft burst will stagger every spider that has breached the surface, buying the party a round of free stomping.
WAVE 4 — THE SILENCE (Minutes 20-30)
No enemies. The spiders stop. The lift grinds upward through empty, dark shaft. The crimson lights are behind them — up here, near the city level, the shaft is lit only by the platform's own emergency strips. Dim bronze light. The sound of the mechanism. Breathing.
The trap: There IS no trap. This is genuine respite. But the party doesn't know that. After three waves of escalating assault, the sudden silence is more frightening than any enemy. Let them sit in it. Let them check their FP. Let them realize how depleted they are.
What they hear: The grinding of the lift mechanism. The distant echo of the tonal alarm, far below. Their own breathing. And from above — from the city level they're approaching — a sound. Faint. Growing louder. Thousands of small metal legs on bronze flooring. A sound like heavy rain on a tin roof, if the rain was made of brass and electricity.
GEAR: Very quiet for the first time. His eye dims to a low amber. Then:
"I should mention. The city-level maintenance population consists of approximately eleven thousand Spider Worker units. They have been operating on autonomous maintenance routines for four millennia. They are now operating on biological purge routines."
Pause.
"The corridor between the Deep Lift and the Surface Lift is approximately four hundred meters."
Pause.
"I would recommend running."

ESCAPE PHASE 3: MZINCHALEFT CITY — THE SWARM
Location: The Mzinchaleft city level. The same pristine corridors they walked through hours ago — the living quarters, the workshops, the dining hall, the transit hub.
The visual: The corridors are not empty anymore. The floor is MOVING. Every Spider Worker in the city — the janitors, the pipe-checkers, the valve-tighteners, the ones that were ignoring them on the way in — has been repurposed. They pour through the corridors in a bronze tide, legs clicking, static crackling, moving with unified purpose toward the Deep Lift exit.
Read aloud:
"The lift locks into the city-level docking bay. The corridor ahead — the same wide, amber-lit hallway you explored in wonder hours ago — is unrecognizable. The floor is a carpet of bronze. Thousands of Dwemer Spider Workers, each the size of a dog, scuttling over and around each other in a flowing, electric mass. The made beds, the set plates, the wrench on the bench — all buried under a tide of clicking, sparking metal.
They are moving TOWARD you. Not fast. Not slow. The speed of a rising flood.
The Surface Lift is four hundred meters ahead. Through that."
THE SWARM MECHANIC
Do NOT roll for individual spiders. The swarm is an environmental hazard. The party must traverse four hundred meters of occupied corridor.
Structure: The corridor is broken into 4 SEGMENTS of 100 meters each. Each segment requires one round of group action to cross.
Each round: Every character chooses how they are moving through the swarm and makes a single check:
