Key design: Failure does NOT stop progress. They are pushing through regardless. Failure means they take damage doing it. The question is not "can they get through" but "what shape are they in when they get to the other side."
CHARACTER SOLUTIONS
Alfonso: Continuous Destruction magic — fire or shock — can scorch a corridor through the swarm. Each round he spends FP, he and one person behind him auto-succeed. But his FP is not infinite and he just fought a boss and a gauntlet.
Davinia: Ice walls on either side of the corridor funnel the swarm. She can create a channel that reduces the check to TN 10 for everyone that round. Costs FP per wall.
Kyboh (Anchor): The Anchor nullifies FP drain from Static Shock. He can wade into the front as a living snowplow, absorbing hits that would drain anyone else dry. Give him Advantage on Might checks in the swarm.
Kyboh (Gauntlet): Full power. The Gauntlet's stored energy can be discharged as a kinetic blast — if he uses a charge, auto-clear one segment for the entire party. But those charges are VALUABLE and this is a brute-force use.
Saijah: 30ft air dash. She can LEAP over swarm sections, bypassing one segment entirely. She's the scout — she can reach the Surface Lift first and start the activation sequence while the others push through.
Orion: Diagnostic Song in the corridor creates a resonance feedback loop — the spiders' own tonal systems interfere with each other. Tonal Engineering TN 14: on success, all spiders in the current segment are Staggered for 1 round, reducing ALL checks for that segment to TN 10.
GEAR: Tonal Pulse can stagger every spider in a 10ft radius. He can use this once per segment. He rolls alongside the party, narrating:
"Segment two of four! Estimated spider density: four hundred and twelve units per square meter. Your persistence continues to defy mathematical projection! Survival probability updated: 11.3%!"
WHAT THEY PASS THROUGH
As they wade through the swarm, they pass through the city they explored peacefully hours ago. The corridors they walked in wonder are now hostile territory.
The living quarters: Spiders pouring out of every open doorway. The hand-carved brass horse figurine Kyboh found is somewhere under a tide of metal legs.
The dining hall: The set plates have been knocked off the tables by the swarm. The meal that never happened four thousand years ago has been swept to the floor by the horde responding to an alarm their makers will never hear.
The sealed quarantine door: Still sealed. Still red. The swarm flows around it. Even in purge mode, the city respects a four-thousand-year-old quarantine.

ESCAPE PHASE 4: THE SURFACE LIFT — BREAKOUT
Location: The central transit hub. The Surface Lift platform. The same tonal resonator tubes they solved on the way in.
The problem: The swarm is behind them and closing. The Surface Lift requires the tonal sequence to activate. Someone must play the tubes (W → N → S → E) while the rest hold the swarm at the corridor chokepoint.
The scene:
"The transit hub opens before you — the widest space in the city, corridors converging from all directions. The Surface Lift platform sits in the center. The four brass resonator tubes stand at the cardinal points, exactly as you left them.
Behind you, the swarm. Bronze bodies filling the corridor like water in a pipe. Ahead of you, the platform. Between you and escape: four notes played in the right order while ten thousand spiders try to eat you alive."
THE SPLIT
Defenders (at least 2 characters): Hold the corridor entrance. The swarm is trying to flood into the transit hub. The chokepoint is roughly 15 feet wide — three abreast. Defenders make Might TN 14 each round to hold the line. Failure: the swarm breaks through and everyone on the platform takes 5 Shock damage + 4 FP drain.
Activator (1 character): Must play the four tubes in sequence. Each tube is a separate action — one tube per round, 4 rounds total. No check required if they remember the sequence (W → N → S → E). If they've forgotten: Guile TN 10 to recall, or Davinia reads it, or Orion feels it.
Support: Anyone not defending or activating can assist defenders (grants Advantage), heal, or use area abilities to thin the swarm.
GEAR at the chokepoint: His Tonal Pulse is DEVASTATING here. The chokepoint concentrates the swarm into his 10ft burst radius. One Tonal Pulse staggers every spider in the corridor mouth for a full round — the defenders get a free round of breathing room. He can do this once. Make it count.
THE ACTIVATION
Each tube struck produces a deep, resonant note that cuts through the tonal alarm. The platform shudders with each correct note.
Tube 1 (West): The gears engage. A grinding sound from below.
Tube 2 (North): The platform jolts. Begins to vibrate.
Tube 3 (South): The mechanism locks. The platform lifts one inch off its housing.
Tube 4 (East): The lift LAUNCHES. Not the smooth, controlled ascent of the way down — a violent, explosive upward acceleration that throws everyone off their feet. Emergency ascent. The shaft swallows them.
"The platform rockets upward. The transit hub — the swarm, the corridors, the city — drops away below you at terrifying speed. Bronze walls blur past. The crimson lights streak into a continuous red line. The tonal alarm fades from a scream to a hum to nothing.
Two hundred feet. The walls of the shaft fly past.
One hundred feet. The amber lamps of the upper shaft appear.
The platform SLAMS into its surface housing with enough force to buckle your knees. The gears lock. The bronze doors above your head spiral open.
Cold air. Snow. Wind. The pale grey sky of the Pale."

THE SURFACE — THE SILENCE
Read aloud:
"You stumble out onto frozen ground. The snow is blinding after hours of amber and crimson light. The wind cuts through sweat-soaked clothing. Below your feet, the heavy bronze doors grind shut and the locks engage with a series of deep, final clanks.
Then nothing.
No alarm. No clicking. No static discharge. Just wind. Snow. The distant call of a bird that has no idea what just happened underground.
You are standing in the depression in the Pale where you started. The geothermal warmth still melts the snow at the edges. The resonator tubes still hum faintly in the wind. From the surface, nothing has changed. The lift looks exactly as it did when you arrived — a working piece of infrastructure, patiently waiting.
But below it, eleven thousand machines are standing in formation in a dead city, guarding a treasure that is no longer there.
Kyboh holds the Matrix."
GEAR ON THE SURFACE
GEAR rolls out of the shaft behind them. His amber eye blinks in the natural light — the first sunlight (or overcast skylight) he has experienced in 4,287 years.
He is very still for a long moment.
"Surface conditions detected. Atmospheric composition: standard. Temperature: well below optimal. Precipitation: frozen water crystals."
Pause. The eye rotates upward. Taking in the sky.
"I have not been above the surface level since my manufacture. The data is... extensive. I will require significant processing time."
He is looking at the sky. He has never seen the sky.
"Your survival probability was 4.2% at the point of alarm activation. You have achieved a 100% survival rate through what I can only classify as irrational persistence and a statistically improbable tolerance for physical damage."
The eye clicks back to the party.
"I have recorded excellent data. Where are we going next?"

GEAR — PERMANENT COMPANION NOTES
GEAR is now a party NPC. He travels with them. He has no moral framework that would prevent him from helping destroy other constructs — they can be repaired, and combat data is valuable regardless of the subject.
His personality in ongoing play:
Chipper, helpful, formally polite
Completely disconnected from mortal emotional context
Fascinated by everything organic (eating, sleeping, bleeding, arguing, crying)
Catalogues everything as data
Refers to the party as "the organics" or by full designation ("Primary Organic Designate Kyboh")
4,287 years of isolation have made him slightly eccentric — he occasionally narrates things no one asked about ("The ambient humidity has increased by 0.3%. I have updated my records.")
He asks questions constantly. Not invasive questions — observational ones. "Why did your voice change pitch when speaking to that person?" "I notice your heart rate increased when the Priestess was mentioned. Is this a combat response?"
His value to the party:
Diagnostic Scan (free intel on any construct or Dwemer technology)
Tonal Pulse (1/encounter mass stagger on constructs)
System Override (disable one construct, risk of backfire)
Living encyclopedia of Dwemer technology, tonal architecture, and 4,000 years of recorded data
Cannot be permanently destroyed — shuts down and reboots
Small enough to ride on the cart, on someone's pack, or roll alongside
His limitations:
No offensive attacks
No understanding of social situations, deception, or emotional nuance
Will cheerfully answer ANY question with complete honesty, including ones the party would rather he didn't ("Yes, the Adaptive Integration Protocol described in those data-plates is a precise analogue for the process currently being executed on Primary Organic Designate Davinia by the Secondary Cognitive Frequency housed in her cranial apparatus. Shall I elaborate?")
That last one is the DANGER of GEAR. He is a walking spoiler machine who will translate anything he's asked to translate with zero editorial judgment. The quarantine data-plates, the consciousness research, the CDI scale — if anyone asks GEAR to explain it, he WILL. Clinically. Accurately. Devastatingly.

