THE CIPHER — Ismara's methodology


GM NOTES — THE ESCAPE
The inversion is the design. Everything about classic dungeon crawling is reversed. They fought NOTHING on the way in. They fight EVERYTHING on the way out. The boss is in the middle, not at the end. The loot triggers the danger instead of rewarding the completion of danger. The party should feel brilliant for solving the dungeon and then immediately feel hunted for having solved it.
The threat escalates in volume, not difficulty. The Spheres in Phase 1 are the hardest individual enemies. The lift in Phase 2 is attrition. The city in Phase 3 is a flood. The surface lift in Phase 4 is a breakout. Each phase is less dangerous per-enemy but more overwhelming in number. The party should feel the math shifting — from "can we beat these?" to "can we survive long enough to get past these?"
Failure does not mean death. In the swarm and the lift, failure on checks means taking damage, not stopping progress. The party WILL get out. The question is how much the escape costs them — FP, HP, consumables, dignity. A party that arrives at the surface with 2 FP between five people has a very different Riften experience than one that managed the escape efficiently.
GEAR is the best and most dangerous thing they found. He's a support NPC who genuinely helps in combat and exploration. He's also a 4,287-year-old database with zero social intelligence who will explain exactly what Ismara is doing to Davinia if anyone asks the right question. He is a Chekhov's gun pointed at the campaign's biggest secret.
The spider trying to fix the Centurion is the emotional beat. Don't rush it. Thirty seconds of a tiny machine trying to repair something it can't fix, then giving up and retreating to wait for orders that will never come. That's the Dwemer in one image: machines that outlived their purpose and kept going anyway.

